===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/mɪə/}}

===Etymology 1===
Old English [[mere#Old English|mere]], from Germanic ''*mariz'', from Indo-European ''*mori''.  Cognate with Dutch [[meer]], German [[Meer]], Norwegian [[mar]]; and (''from Indo-European'') with Latin [[mare#Latin|mare]], Breton [[mor#Breton|mor]], Russian [[море]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun|mere|meres}}
# ''(obsolete)'' The [[sea]].
# (''dialectal or literary'') A pool or lake; a marsh.

===Etymology 2===
Old English [[mære|mǣre]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun|mere|meres}}
# A [[boundary]]; a boundary-marker.

===Etymology 3===
Anglo-Norman [[meer]], from Old French [[mier]], from Latin [[merus]].

====Adjective====
{{en-ad2|'''mere'''|-|'''[[merest]]'''}}
#just, only; the smallest amount
#:''I saved a mere 10 pounds this week.''

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈmɛri/}}

===Etymology 4===
Maori [[mere#Maori|mere]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun|mere|meres}}
